Use this when a release of any SemVer bump is starting or in flight — from the first kickoff message up to handing off to closure. The lifecycle orchestrates a release end-to-end and wraps per-task implementation; for how an individual task within the Implementation stage is scoped/specced/executed, use skill `sdh-phase-workflow`. Two self-contained pieces are extracted into their own skills: **closure** (9→10-step checklist + git canon) — `sdh-release-closure`; **retro** — `sdh-retro`.

Stages are **soft** — the assistant does not gate transitions strictly, but it **must announce** transitions in chat. Trivial fast-lane tasks (per skill `sdh-phase-workflow`) bypass the lifecycle entirely.

## Light track vs full

The fork is decided at the **Analysis** stage, by bump class + number of decisions:

- **Light track** — if the bump is **PATCH**, OR **MINOR with no cross-boundary change and <3 non-obvious decisions**. Collapsed path: Request → Analysis → spec-as-chat → Implementation → Test → Closure → Retro. The **Plan and Plan-review stages are folded into Analysis** by default (tasks straight into `docs/todo.md`, no separate plan-review) — **without** per-stage "may I skip?".
- **Full track** — **MAJOR always**, plus **MINOR with real design / cross-boundary** (DB schema, contracts, security-sensitive code). All 11 stages.

The boundary is a point of design judgment, not file count (see "what counts as a decision" in `sdh-phase-workflow`). Unsure between light and full → take full.

## Autonomous mode (an overlay on either track)

Orthogonal to scope — it overlays both light and full. The essence: **a single front-loaded gate at design acceptance, then an autonomous run with no per-stage approvals.**

- **When to offer:** all the judgment is settled at design/spec — the rest is mechanical follow-through. Typical for client / landing / visual work (the accepted mockup `sdh-visual-mockups` is the gate).
- **How it turns on:** at spec/mockup acceptance (stage 4c) the assistant offers: *"design accepted, the rest is mechanical — I'll run Implementation → Test → the documentation part of Closure without approvals, only announcing transitions. OK?"* The grant is the user's. A standing "work without stopping" directive = pre-granted.
- **What runs autonomously:** stages 5–8 + the documentation part of Closure (bump, Changelog, done.md, closure commit on dev).
- **Always a stop, even in autonomous mode:** two interactive gates survive the autonomous run. (1) For **client / landing / any visual surface** — the user's **visual sign-off** at Test (they look at the built or running UI and approve) before Closure proceeds. (2) The git canon block (tag / master-merge / master-push) is user-only. Never emit the git block before the visual is approved, and emit it **once** — then wait, don't re-post it each turn. A server / tool / microservice whose smoke is automated has no visual gate (its smoke self-verifies) — autonomous mode there runs straight to the git block.
- **Exit from the mode (re-engage):** a new non-obvious decision, a blocker, scope grew → re-evaluate the bump class, smoke revealed a problem → announce a loop back; afterward the autonomous mode may be offered again.

## Task filing — always the roadmap, never a backlog

Every task written to `docs/todo.md` goes **under a `## vX.Y.Z` release header** — the version you expect to ship it in. There is **no flat "Backlog" bucket**, no unsorted pile: a task with no version is invisible on the roadmap and quietly rots. Sort on capture, not "later". This applies to *every* task — planned in a release (stage 5), carried over (stage 10), or captured ad-hoc mid-session.

The **only** uncertainty allowed is **timing relative to the next MAJOR**. If you genuinely cannot pin the exact minor/patch, still place the task on the timeline at MAJOR granularity: under your best-guess pre-MAJOR version, or under a coarse `## vN.0.0` (or later) section for work deferred past the next major. "In scope before the next major, or after it?" is the single legitimate open question — answer it and file the task under the matching header. Never leave a task unsorted.

## Stages

1. **Request** — the user's kickoff for a release scope, feature batch, or non-trivial task.
2. **Analysis** — the assistant estimates scope, classifies fast-lane vs phase and light vs full track, surfaces blockers/dependencies, and for features needing server endpoints runs the pre-flight surface check (skill `sdh-api-contract-consume`). **The bump class (PATCH/MINOR/MAJOR) and version number are decided here** — not deferred to closure: the `## vX.Y.Z` header in the Plan must be right from the start. MAJOR/MINOR is confirmed with the user here (the "ask before MAJOR/MINOR" rule fires at Analysis). Output: a one-message scope picture + class + version the user confirms or redirects.
3. **Spec** — a written spec per the spec step of `sdh-phase-workflow` (or thread-as-spec). Includes context, scope, files-to-modify, decisions, and a `## Verification` section. *(Light track: the chat itself serves as the spec.)* **For non-server features with a visual surface — do mockups first (skill `sdh-visual-mockups`); the accepted mockup carries the design decisions, the spec text can be thin.**
4. **Spec review** — three-step procedure:
   - (a) **Assistant self-review** — an explicit pass: ambiguities, contradictions, logical gaps, missing files-to-modify, mismatched symbol names, missing i18n cleanup, missing test updates. Report to chat (or *"no issues"*).
   - (b) **Clarification questions** — only if real ones emerged from (a); don't invent for show.
   - (c) **User OK** — explicit approval. At least one full self-review + OK pass is mandatory before any plan or implementation.
5. **Plan** *(full track)* — task breakdown into `docs/todo.md` (id, effort, priority), under the `## vX.Y.Z — ...` confirmed at Analysis — **never a flat backlog** (see "Task filing"). Each task maps cleanly to a spec decision or verification step. *(Light track: folded into Analysis.)*
6. **Plan review** *(full track)* — same three-step procedure (4a/4b/4c). Self-review: scope alignment with the spec, missing/over-broad tasks, priority/effort sanity, order/dependencies. *(Light track: folded into Analysis.)*
7. **Implementation** — task by task per the implementation step of `sdh-phase-workflow`, using the project's implementation workflow. Each completed task moves from `docs/todo.md` to `docs/done.md`.
8. **Test** — manual smoke per the spec's `## Verification` + automated suites (`cargo test`, `npm test`, `npm run check`). **Test counts and pass/fail go into Changelog only AFTER the real smoke, never from progress notes.** A bug surfacing here or at closure — see the late-catch rule in `sdh-release-closure` (a small confident fix folds into the current release).
   - **Visual sign-off gate (client / landing / any visual surface).** For a release whose changes are visual, the smoke **is the user eyeballing the actual built/running UI** — automated suites and the assistant's self-review do **not** substitute for it. **Closure does not start and the git canon block is not shown until the user explicitly approves the visual.** This gate holds even in autonomous mode. Present the closure git block **once**, after that approval — re-posting it before sign-off just makes the user run the same tag/merge commands repeatedly. *(Server / tool / microservice releases self-verify via automated smoke — no visual gate; run straight to the git block.)*
   - **Preprod smoke access (projects with a deployed preprod + auth).** Keep a `.env.preprod` holding the credentials to *log in* to preprod for the smoke: the admin-panel key and the project/user keys you smoke as. For OTP auth, also a smoke email + a cached refresh token so you don't re-run OTP on every login. **This is access for smoking, NOT the secret set that *launches* preprod** — the common mix-up: `.env.preprod` gets you *inside* to click through the changes, while the deploy/runtime secrets *boot* the environment. Don't conflate them. The file is secret — under `.gitignore` (`.env.*`), never committed. *(N/A to projects with no deployed preprod / no auth, e.g. desktop tools.)*
9. **Closure** — full checklist + git canon: skill `sdh-release-closure`. The tag command is the user's action.
10. **Next-release plan** — a **light re-estimation and re-slicing**, NOT a design session. This stage is expected at every closure (it's cheap — minutes) so don't skip it, but don't balloon it either. Re-read the tasks already filed under the next `## vX.Y.Z` header(s) and: re-check effort/priority against what this release just taught you, split any task that has outgrown its estimate, drop or merge ones this release made moot, and confirm the next version's scope with the user. **Do NOT spec, brainstorm, or design here** — no files-to-modify, no decisions, no "phase 2 of the next release". If a task turns out to need real design, that belongs to the *next* release's Spec stage, not this one. Output: the next `## vX.Y.Z` section, re-estimated and re-sliced (still on the roadmap — see "Task filing").
11. **Retro** — a structured retrospective: skill `sdh-retro`.

## Stage transitions

- The assistant announces each transition: **"moving from stage <X> to stage <Y>"**.
- Skipping a stage (in the full track) requires explicit permission: *"can I go straight to impl?" / "no retro this time?"* — the assistant proposes the skip with a one-line reason; the user acks or declines. Default — **no skipping**. *(The light track already folds Plan/Plan-review by default — that's not a "skip", it's the track.)*
- **Loops back to an earlier stage are allowed but not default.** The chain runs forward by default. A loop (impl reveals a gap → back to Spec for an amendment → re-run Spec-review → resume Implementation) happens on user request or when circumstances force it (new constraint, missing endpoint surface, broken assumption, **scope grew → re-evaluate bump class**). The assistant announces loops the same way: *"a gap surfaced, moving from stage 7 back to stage 3, ok?"* — the user acks. Without an explicit loop announcement, the lifecycle is strictly forward.
